        <h1 class="headline headline--normal">Herniated Disc</h1>
        <p>
          A herniated disc occurs when the outer layer of cartilage fails and
          opens which allows the softer inner cartilage to protrude out
          laterally of centrally of the disc.
        </p>

        <p>
          Another term for a herniated disc is a disc rupture or slipped disc,
          although the whole disc cannot slip. A small area which is crack is
          normally affected.
        </p>

        <p>
          A bulging disc is less likely to cause pain when compared to a
          herniated disc. A herniated disc generally protrudes farther and is
          much more likely to irritate spinal nerves. Painful inflammation of
          the nerve root can occur following a disc herniation, as the disc
          compresses the nerve which results in painful irritation.
        </p>

        <p>
          Inflammation and swelling are common from the extruded liquid from the
          nucleus pulposus
        </p>

        <p>
          An MRI is normally required to diagnose a herniated disc. Some people
          with low back pain will have imaging testing that indicates that they
          do not have a herniated disc. Therefore, it maybe a muscle injury or
          weak core causing the pain.
        </p>
